Mafdet is a fortified harbor city where the Saltglass Reach meets the open sea, named after a pre-Keeper coastal ritual figure: a swift feline executioner who punished thieves and oath-breakers. The city is the eastern ocean gate of the continent's central trade system and the only port where inland desert law and maritime contract law are operationally integrated daily. Pre-Keeper Strand Folk maintained beacon fires and anti-pirate patrols before interior civilizations reached the coast; they established the philosophical principle that the beach itself is a legal boundary between two kinds of law, reconciled through negotiation witnessed by the guardian. The Strandline Compact — forged during the Fracture Era when inland authority collapsed — established three principles: harbor first (no political decision may obstruct port operations), dual attestation (no cargo enters or leaves without verification under both inland and maritime standards), swift judgment (commercial disputes resolved within three tides). Three operational blocs govern: Harbor Wardens (quay security, anti-piracy, harbor chain — a bronze-and-iron chain raised every night at dusk), Ledger Houses (four Houses: Tide Ledger Hall for bulk commodity certification and Saltweight standard, Shoreward House for inland-maritime conversion, Storm Ledger for insurance and escrow, Quarantine Ledger for relic and hazardous cargo), and Sand-Sea Carters' Guild (overland linkage to oasis corridors, waystations along the Reach). The Shrine of the First Claw maintains the Oath Chamber, Swift Court (cases heard within three tides), and Claw Mark Registry. Mafdet and Midgaard are the two major authentication poles for high-value antiquities: Midgaard dominates inland registry prestige; Mafdet dominates maritime export legitimacy.

